  "body": "Consider the following println:\n\n``` rust\n    let msg = \"Hello\";\n    println!(\"(i,j,k): |{:30}|\", msg);\n```\n\nThis is using the `width` parameter to ensure that the output occupies _at least_ `width` characters. (One can provide other arguments like fill/alignment to adjust the fill character or whether the output is left/right/center- alligned.)  See docs here: https://doc.rust-lang.org/std/fmt/#width\n\nIn other words, it prints this (note the distance between the two occurrences of `|`):\n\n```\n(i,j,k): |Hello                         |\n```\n\nSo, the problem:\n\nThe `Debug` trait seems to honor `width` for numeric and pointer types, but not for other types.\n\nFor example: \n\n``` rust\n    println!(\"(i,j,k): |{:30?}|\", msg);\n```\n\ndoes not necessarily put at least 30 characters between the two `|` characters that it prints; in the case of `msg` given above, it prints:\n\n```\n(i,j,k): |\"Hello\"|\n```\n\nHere is a [playpen](http://is.gd/NGt8cW) illustrating the problem on several inputs.\n",
